         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          It\xe2\x80\x99s no wonder. One
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/38ce1354-49ba-4b23-8c7e-fac1f4090de2?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
          Hacker News commenter
         </a>
         <span>
          compared learning COBOL to \xe2\x80\x9cswallowing a barbed cube shaped pill,\xe2\x80\x9d but cheerfully pointed out that that\xe2\x80\x99s not the hard part.
         </span>
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="763">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://substack.com/redirect/8de5ebc8-0d5c-46a7-81d7-9390f00a6795?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="align-items: center; border: none; display: block; flex-direction: column; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; position: relative; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/290c07db-5bbc-4249-ac94-d427f8faa91c_763x111.png","srcNoWatermark":null,"fullscreen":null,"imageSize":null,"height":111,"width":763,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null,"belowTheFold":true,"topImage":false,"internalRedirect":null}' height="80.01310615989514" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1526,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F290c07db-5bbc-4249-ac94-d427f8faa91c_763x111.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100% !important; vertical-align: middle; width: auto !important;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Even worse, the ones who
         </span>
         <em>
          really
         </em>
         <span>
          know how things work, like Neil Stepanich, are even older and no longer in the workforce. Reuters begins a
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/100af537-12b8-49e1-88f0-b20db6446ae1?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
          great 2017 piece on the \xe2\x80\x9cCOBOL Cowboys\xe2\x80\x9d
         </a>
         <span>
          by writing, \xe2\x80\x9cBill Hinshaw is not a typical 75-year-old. He divides his time between his family \xe2\x80\x93 he has 32 grandchildren and great-grandchildren \xe2\x80\x93 and helping U.S. companies avert crippling computer meltdowns.\xe2\x80\x9d
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Hinshaw and his wife founded a company called
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/4cfcf33a-4150-48fe-84d7-100ba62521c4?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
          COBOL Cowboys
         </a>
         <span>
          , named after the movie
         </span>
         <em>
          Space Cowboys
         </em>
         <span>
          in which retired Air Force pilots are brought in to troubleshoot a problem in space that only they know how to solve.
         </span>
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="788">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://substack.com/redirect/052b584f-3a6b-4c79-a588-967026219d31?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="align-items: center; border: none; display: block; flex-direction: column; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; position: relative; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b37d9541-5d45-4b73-adaf-9ca379e51fc6_788x446.png","srcNoWatermark":null,"fullscreen":null,"imageSize":null,"height":446,"width":788,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null,"belowTheFold":true,"topImage":false,"internalRedirect":null}' height="311.29441624365484" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1576,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb37d9541-5d45-4b73-adaf-9ca379e51fc6_788x446.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100% !important; vertical-align: middle; width: auto !important;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
          <figcaption class="image-caption" style="box-sizing: content-box; color: #808080; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: -.15px; line-height: 20px; margin-top: 8px; padding-left: 15%; padding-right: 15%; text-align: center; width: 70%;">
           <em>
            Space Cowboys (2000)
           </em>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         The challenge, according to Hinshaw, is even though some young people still learn COBOL, there are some things you just can\xe2\x80\x99t teach: \xe2\x80\x9cCOBOL-based systems vary widely and original programmers rarely wrote handbooks, making trouble-shooting difficult for others.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Only people who were there when the systems were built know how it all fits together, and worse, that dwindling group of people won\xe2\x80\x99t be around forever.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Accenture\xe2\x80\x99s Andrew Starrs put it bluntly. The risk is \xe2\x80\x9cnot so much that an individual may have retired," he says, but that "he may have
         </span>
         <strong>
          expired
         </strong>
         <span>
          , so there is no option to get him or her to come back."
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         What happens when the COBOL Cowboys ride into that eternal sunset?
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         There will be no one left who knows how the infrastructure on which trillions of dollars daily all fits together, no one to fix it when its inevitable crumble accelerates. COBOL is incredibly impressive infrastructure, but even the best infrastructure is no match for time.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         So why aren\xe2\x80\x99t the banks getting ahead of the problem and doing whatever they can to avoid catastrophic risk?
        </p>
        <h4 class="header-with-anchor-widget" style="-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.125em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;">
         <strong>
          Cow-Paced Banks
         </strong>
        </h4>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         The short answer is that replacing the COBOL-based systems while the bank runs on them is slow, expensive, and introduces short-term risks.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/508b1a11-942b-4199-8e22-93652989de2d?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
          Chris Pento
         </a>
         <span>
          , Clear Street\xe2\x80\x99s CEO and co-founder, has spent his career in operations at financial institutions, from large established investment banks like Merrill Lynch to startup broker dealers like Exos Financial. If anyone feels the brunt of bad systems, it\xe2\x80\x99s the operations people who are responsible for cleaning up their mess every day.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         I asked Chris why a big bank couldn\xe2\x80\x99t just throw a bunch of money at the problem. He told me they probably could build new systems, before listing off a litany of reasons they wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-top: 0; padding: 0;">
         <li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">
           Building the system while running a company with diverse needs \xe2\x80\x93 including keeping clients happy on a daily basis \xe2\x80\x93 adds complexity
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">
           Technical debt has built up in these systems over 30 to 40 years as people patch problems
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">
           There\xe2\x80\x99s all these connection points \xe2\x80\x93 internally and with external systems \xe2\x80\x93 that have to be unconnected and reconnected, \xe2\x80\x9cand it takes five years just to figure out what the connections are.\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">
           Then, midway through the process, someone on the risk team says, \xe2\x80\x9cHey, you forgot about this\xe2\x80\x9d and shuts the project down.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cYou drive on the BQE (Brooklyn-Queens Expressway),\xe2\x80\x9d he said. \xe2\x80\x9cYou know how bad decade-long projects can get.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          The complexity and time to build it is hard and long, fraught with risk. Recall the patchwork of integrations we talked about earlier, integrations with the DTCC, OCC, exchanges, and regulators, in countries around the world and on a variety of computer systems. Like a game of
         </span>
         <em>
          Operation
         </em>
         <span>
          , touching any one of them the wrong way might mean game over, so you have to go very slowly and very carefully, all while protecting the core.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Jon Daplyn, who was responsible for these systems at Morgan Stanley, echoed Chris\xe2\x80\x99 assessment and added a technical lens. To Jon, the issue is that, while the banks have tried to improve their systems, they\xe2\x80\x99ve only gotten so far because they\xe2\x80\x99re afraid to touch the core and break the whole thing.
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;">
         <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;">
          <em>
           <span>
            What you\xe2\x80\x99d have to do is take a small piece of functionality from the core, pull it out and rebuild it, and then bridge it back in until the core gets smaller and smaller. Thousands of people have been building and patching and patching, never really changing the core because they\xe2\x80\x99re too scared. Pulling it apart will take
           </span>
           <strong>
            decades
           </strong>
           <span>
            of consistent effort.
           </span>
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Decades may as well be millennia from the perspective of the people running the banks today: they would need to foot the bill under their watch for a payoff that
         </span>
         <em>
          might
         </em>
         <span>
          come long after they\xe2\x80\x99ve sailed into retirement. So they take the hidden but pernicious risk that comes with inaction.
         </span>
        </p>
        <h3 class="header-with-anchor-widget" style="-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;">
         <strong>
          What Happens When the Infrastructure Breaks?
         </strong>
         <span>
         </span>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         The big risk in the old system is that the different people who need to see the same data, don\xe2\x80\x99t.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Do you have a single source of truth? Is there one place where your firm calculates the value of an option or many? Do your finance team, risk team, and the client all see the same values or do they see different values? Do they see the same thing eventually, or in real-time?
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Sometimes, bad infrastructure shows up as potholes. Slower transactions, extra work for the back office, miscalculated fees like Uri dealt with. Annoying and inefficient, but not the end of the world.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Other times, it rears its head in the financial equivalent of a bridge collapsing with drivers on it.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="768">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://substack.com/redirect/a04bca49-3fce-41a3-9139-c763bd26f2a4?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="align-items: center; border: none; display: block; flex-direction: column; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; position: relative; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b6ce26c5-8c18-4e13-95a7-2aa22231a535_768x436.png","srcNoWatermark":null,"fullscreen":null,"imageSize":null,"height":436,"width":768,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null,"belowTheFold":true,"topImage":false,"internalRedirect":null}' height="312.2395833333333" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1536,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb6ce26c5-8c18-4e13-95a7-2aa22231a535_768x436.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100% !important; vertical-align: middle; width: auto !important;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
          <figcaption class="image-caption" style="box-sizing: content-box; color: #808080; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: -.15px; line-height: 20px; margin-top: 8px; padding-left: 15%; padding-right: 15%; text-align: center; width: 70%;">
           <em>
            I-95 Bridge Collapse, NBC News
           </em>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Like when
         </span>
         <strong>
          Archegos Capital Management
         </strong>
         <span>
          blew up and took
         </span>
         <strong>
          Credit Suisse
         </strong>
         <span>
          down with it.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Remember this one?
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         In March 2021, ViacomCBS sold some stock and its stock tanked. That was bad news for Archegos, Bill Hwang\xe2\x80\x99s $10 billion family office, which was turbo long swaps on ViacomCBS and a number of other tech stocks on margin extended by the fund\xe2\x80\x99s prime brokers. As the prices fell, the prime brokers demanded more collateral.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="908">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://substack.com/redirect/c0356aee-83f6-465b-99e5-23e4e1c15f74?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="align-items: center; border: none; display: block; flex-direction: column; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; position: relative; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/3bedaeec-0899-4c26-bd88-698dfd5da881_908x608.png","srcNoWatermark":null,"fullscreen":null,"imageSize":null,"height":608,"width":908,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":815573,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":"image/png","href":null,"belowTheFold":true,"topImage":false,"internalRedirect":null}' height="368.2819383259912" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1816,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F3bedaeec-0899-4c26-bd88-698dfd5da881_908x608.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100% !important; vertical-align: middle; width: auto !important;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
          <figcaption class="image-caption" style="box-sizing: content-box; color: #808080; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: -.15px; line-height: 20px; margin-top: 8px; padding-left: 15%; padding-right: 15%; text-align: center; width: 70%;">
           <em>
            Archegos\xe2\x80\x99 Bill Hwang outside a federal courthouse, Reuters
           </em>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         When Archegos failed to meet its margin call, its prime brokers \xe2\x80\x93 including Credit Suisse, Nomura, Goldman Sachs, and Morgan Stanley, among others \xe2\x80\x93 raced to sell off Archegos\xe2\x80\x99 collateral and recoup their money, crushing the prices of the assets they all held.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Archegos collapsed, of course, and it brought some, but not all, of its prime brokers with it. As
         </span>
         <em>
          <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/3a934a21-dad2-4583-95eb-e8dc4647cafb?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
           The Trade News
          </a>
         </em>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/3a934a21-dad2-4583-95eb-e8dc4647cafb?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
          reported
         </a>
         <span>
          , speed made all the difference. And speed depended on risk management systems.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         When Archegos blew up, Goldman had the intel within seconds, Morgan Stanley hesitated but sold on the same day, and Credit Suisse, which was still on antiquated risk management systems, waited days to catastrophic effect.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Goldman was the first to sell. Over the course of the day on March 26th, \xe2\x80\x9cGoldman Sachs sold $10 billion of shares in stocks linked to Archegos.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;">
         <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;">
          <em>
           <span>
            \xe2\x80\x9cWe have
           </span>
           <strong>
            robust risk management
           </strong>
           <span>
            that governs the amount of financing we provide for these types of portfolios,\xe2\x80\x9d said David Solomon, CEO of Goldman Sachs, on the bank\xe2\x80\x99s first quarter 2021 earnings call. \xe2\x80\x9cWe identified the risk early and took prompt action consistent with the terms of our contract with the client.\xe2\x80\x9d
           </span>
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Morgan Stanley was almost as quick, dumping $8 billion that same day. The firm lost $911 million between money owed by Archegos and trading losses. A mere scratch.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Nomura wasn\xe2\x80\x99t as lucky. It lost $2.87 billion in the winddown.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          But the biggest loser was Credit Suisse. The Swiss bank was the slowest to appreciate and unwind its exposure to Archegos, and lost a nauseating
         </span>
         <strong>
          $5.5 billion
         </strong>
         <span>
          . It had to raise $1.9 billion to stay afloat, and fired both its investment bank CEO Brian Chin and, tellingly, its Chief Risk and Compliance Officer, Lara Werner.
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t enough. Two years later, in March 2023, the Swiss Government and Swiss Financial Market Supervisory Authority organized the $3.2 billion fire sale of Credit Suisse to its Swiss Rival, UBS.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cCredit Suisse would be here today,\xe2\x80\x9d Uri told me, \xe2\x80\x9cif they\xe2\x80\x99d had the right tech in place.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          Or take
         </span>
         <strong>
          Signature Bank
         </strong>
         <span>
          .
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         The same month that UBS acquired Credit Suisse, March 2023, Signature Bank faced a bank run as depositors raced to withdraw their funds on the heels of the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         As the FDIC went to work to assess the damage, they asked all of the at-risk banks for tallies of the wires they had going out.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Signature Bank said, essentially, \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re actually not sure because of our systems.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         The FDIC said, essentially, \xe2\x80\x9cAre you kidding me?\xe2\x80\x9d and told the New York State Department of Financial Services to take possession of the bank that Sunday.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          The bank\xe2\x80\x99s exposure to crypto was blamed in the press, but as the FDIC wrote in its report, \xe2\x80\x9cSBNY management was sometimes slow to respond to FDIC\xe2\x80\x99s supervisory concerns and
         </span>
         <strong>
          did not prioritize appropriate risk management practices and internal controls
         </strong>
         <span>
          . Management was described by FDIC supervisors as
         </span>
         <strong>
          reactive, rather than proactive
         </strong>
         <span>
          , in addressing bank risks and supervisory concerns.\xe2\x80\x9d
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          The real challenge that affected these firms is a
         </span>
         <strong>
          lack of clean data
         </strong>
         <span>
          .
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         At the surface level, that sounds like a silly and trivial-to-fix problem given the stakes. But as we\xe2\x80\x99ve learned, for international firms that handle every asset class, getting clean data means integrating hundreds of systems, all which speak different languages, into one central database that can translate all of that disparate data into clear metrics as fast as digitally possible. When that database is built in a 70-year-old programming language that few people alive truly understand, and when it needs to translate from exchanges, clearing houses, and clients that each speak their own language, the problem becomes prohibitively complex.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Little inconsistencies compound on each other, and as they do, the risks compound, too, until\xe2\x80\xa6 KABOOM.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         These are the kind of risks that Uri thinks are going to come due more and more frequently if the infrastructure isn\xe2\x80\x99t fixed from the core out.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Fixing the infrastructure from the inside \xe2\x80\x93 rebuilding the roads while people are driving on them \xe2\x80\x93 doesn\xe2\x80\x99t seem to be an option. If it were, Clear Street wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t exist.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Rebuilding the infrastructure from the ground up is hard, but it might actually be the easiest way to make sure it happens. That\xe2\x80\x99s Clear Street\xe2\x80\x99s bet.
        </p>
        <h3 class="header-with-anchor-widget" style="-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;">
         <strong>
          What Clear Street is Building
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         A long time horizon is a competitive advantage, one that requires capital, vision, and the right blend of patience and momentum.
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         <span>
          When I wrote about
         </span>
         <a href="https://substack.com/redirect/afcd7979-8344-40d1-91b1-504c93a125cf?j=eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel="" style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">
          Anduril
         </a>
         <span>
          , I said that it was in a
         </span>
         <strong>
          goldilocks position
         </strong>
         <span>
          when it came to acquiring advanced technology companies: \xe2\x80\x9cit\xe2\x80\x99s well-funded enough that it can make meaningful acquisitions, but privately held enough that it doesn\xe2\x80\x99t need to justify its investments in the same way public companies do.\xe2\x80\x9d
         </span>
        </p>
        <p style="color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">
         Clear Street sits in its own goldilocks zone: it\xe2\x80\x99s well-funded and experienced enough that it can build new infrastructure with the patience it requires, but fresh enough that it\xe2\x80\x99s not constrained by the same demands and risks as the banks.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;">
         <figure style="margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" data-component-name="Image2ToDOMStatic" style="mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
